<h2 class="mb-5">Basics</h2>

<h3 class="h5" id="staking">What is staking</h3>
<div class="mb-5">
  <p>
    <strong>Staking</strong> is the process of delegating your SOL tokens to one or more validators, who process transactions and keep the network secure. Validators earn rewards for their services and delegators then get a proportional amount of the rewards less the validator's <a href="#commission">commission</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    In order to delegate your SOL tokens, you need to create a separate stake account and choose a validator to delegate to. You can do it either from <a href="https://docs.solana.com/cli">command line interface</a>
    or by using one of the <a href="https://docs.solana.com/wallet-guide">supported wallets</a>.
  </p>
</div>

<h3 class="h5" id="timeline">Staking timeline</h3>
<div class="mb-5">
  <p>
    After you delegate your SOL tokens, you need to wait until the next <a href="#epoch">epoch</a> for
    the changes to take effect. Throughout the epoch validator is voting and generates new transactions
    according to the leader schedule and only after one entire epoch ends, the reward is added to your staking pool
    and is automatically delegated to the same validator.
  </p>
  <p>
    Please note that during the pending epoch your tokens cannot be withdrawn.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you wish to undelegate your tokens from the validator, you need to wait untill the end of the epoch.
    In this case your last reward will be added to your stake account and will no longer be delegated.
  </p>
</div>

<h3 class="h5" id="choosing-validator">Choosing the right validator</h3>
<div class="mb-5">
  <p>
    There are a couple of things to consider while choosing the right validator to delegate your
    stake to. In order to be able to vote properly and create new transactions it needs to have constant high
    speed network access and good overall performance. Another important thing is the <a href="#commission">commission</a>
    validator takes to cover it's costs - the less the better. You should also check if validator is credible
    and operates in a transparent manner.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Performance</strong> - we're gathering some statistical data to determine how well the validator operates
    within solana network. <a href="#root-distance">Root block distance</a> and <a href="#vote-distance">vote distance</a>
    show how far behind it is from the top of the blockchain while <a href="#skipped-vote">the skipped slot &percnt;</a>
    measures the percent of the time that a leader fails to produce a block during their
    allocated slots.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Commission</strong> - The important thing to notice here is that commissions can be changed in any
    moment, so it's crucial to check for particular validators
    <%= link_to "commission change history", commission_histories_path(network: params[:network]) %> and see if
    there's no malicious behaviour there. Some of the validators are offering 0% commission as an introductory
    offer. It's a good idea to contact them to see when the offer expires and the new rate
    at that time.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Reliability</strong> - if the validator has all the information filled up, has its own website and
    no malicious behaviour in the past is detected it is more likely that it cares about reliability and thus is
    more trustworthy.
  </p>
</div>

<h3 class="h5" id="score">How Does the Validator Score V1 Work?</h3>
<div class="mb-5">
  <p>
    We track validator performance over several dimensions and assign a score in the range of (0..2) for each.
    The scores also correlate with colored icons: <i class="fas fa-circle score-2"></i> is excellent,
    <i class="fas fa-circle score-1"></i> is OK, and <i class="fas fa-circle score-0"></i> means there is room for
    improvement. The scored dimensions are:
  </p>

  <ol class="list-with-numbers">
    <li>
      <strong>Root Block Distance</strong> <br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-2 mr-1"></i> (2 points) means that the validator median block distance is at,
      or below, the cluster median.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-1 mr-1"></i> (1 point) means that the validator average block distance is at,
      or below, the cluster average.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-0 mr-1"></i> (0 points) means that the validator average is higher than
      the cluster average.<br />
      The medians and averages are calculated over a trailing 2-day period and do not reset with each epoch.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Vote Distance</strong> The scoring rules are the same as Root Block Distance above.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Skipped Slot &percnt;</strong> <br />
      For this metric, we track a trailing 24-hour moving average of the skip rate. The moving average (MA) is
      then compared to the cluster median(MA) and cluster average(MA). On the charts, a dotted line shows
      the spot reading that resets with every epoch. The solid line shows the 24-hour moving average.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-2 mr-1"></i> (2 points) means that the validator skipped slot &percnt; is at, or below,
      the cluster median.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-1 mr-1"></i> (1 point) means that the skipped slot &percnt; is at, or below,
      the cluster average.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-0 mr-1"></i> (0 points) means that the validator average is higher than
      the cluster average.<br />
      The moving averages reflect the previous 24-hours, and the spot reading resets with each new epoch.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Published Information</strong><br />
      Investors or delegators want to know who is running a node. The Published Information Score measures
      the contact information that the validator has posted to the blockchain using the
      `solana validator-info` feature.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-2 mr-1"></i> (2 points) means that the validator has published all four data
      elements (Name, Keybase ID, Website URL, and Details).<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-1 mr-1"></i> (1 point) means that the validator has published two or three parts.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-0 mr-1"></i> (0 points) means that the validator has published only one, or zero,
      pieces of contact data.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Software Version</strong><br />
      This score is based on the Solana software version currently in use on this node.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-2 mr-1"></i> (2 points) means that the validator is using the correct major,
      minor, & patch versions.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-1 mr-1"></i> (1 point) means that the validator is using the correct major,
      & minor versions (but not patch).<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-0 mr-1"></i> (0 points) means that the validator is only using the current
      major version (or less).<br />
      This score is updated as soon as the validator starts voting with a new software update.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Security Report</strong><br />
      Security and operations are a critical component of a well-run validator. I am assigning one (1) point
      when a validator has provided me with a URL to their web page related to security policies. Please
      be aware that I am not evaluating the content on that web page. I will merely confirm that the web page
      discusses security or operating procedures before posting the link to this site.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-1 mr-1"></i> (1 point) means that the validator has provided a valid URL.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-0 mr-1"></i> (0 points) means that the validator has not published a description
      of their security policies.<br />
      (Validators, please directly <%= link_to 'contact Brian Long', contact_us_path %> to provide the URL.)
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Stake Concentration</strong> is a contra-score and will DEDUCT points from a validator's total score:<br />
      <i class="fas fa-minus-circle text-warning mr-1"></i> (-2 points) means that this validator is one of
      the top 33&percnt; active stake holders.<br />
      The concentration of stake is a bad thing on a decentralized proof-of-stake blockchain. There is
      no deduction of points, and no icon, if the validator controls less than 3%. If you are an investor who is
      delegating stake, please consider high performing nodes without high stake concentrations.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Data Center Concentration</strong><br />
      This is another contra-score that will DEDUCT points from validators located in data centers that host a high
      percentage of other Solana validators. A high data center concentration means that a problem with
      the hosting provider could take many of the nodes offline.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-minus-circle text-danger mr-1"></i> (-2 points) means that this validator is in a data center
      with a very high percent of the active stake.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-minus-circle text-warning mr-1"></i> (-1 point) means that this validator is in a data center
      with a high percent of the active stake.<br />
      If you are an investor who is delegating stake, please consider high performing nodes without a high data
      center concentration.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Authorized Withdrawer Score</strong><br />
      Validator identity matching authorized withdrawer is a security risk.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-minus-circle text-danger mr-1"></i> (-2 points) means that this validator identity is the same as the authorized withdrawer identity.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-0 mr-1"></i> (0 point) means that that this validator identity is different than the authorized withdrawer identity.<br />
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    The maximum score is currently eleven (11) points:
    <span class="text-nowrap">
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-2" title="Root Distance Score"></i>
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-2" title="Vote Distance Score"></i>
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-2" title="Skipped Slot Score"></i>
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-2" title="Published Information Score"></i>
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-2" title="Software Version Score"></i>
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-1" title="Security Report Score"></i>
    </span>
  </p>
</div>

<h3 class="h5" id="score-v2">How Does the&nbsp;Validator Score V2 Work?</h3>
<div class="mb-5">
  <p>The V2 Score system works similar to V1, with the following exceptions:</p>
  <ol class="list-with-numbers">
    <li>
      <strong>Root Block Distance</strong> <br />
      Validators are divided into <%= @groups_number %> equal groups, depending on their
      performance in&nbsp;current epoch:<br />
      <% score = @max_score %>
      <% @groups_number.times do |index| %>
        <% if index == 0 %>
          <i class="fas fa-circle score-<%= score %> mr-1"></i> (<%= score %> points) means that the&nbsp;validator is in
          the group of 1/<%= @groups_number %> best validators in current epoch.<br />
        <% elsif index == (@max_score) %>
          <i class="fas fa-circle score-<%= score %> mr-1"></i> (<%= score %> points) means that the&nbsp;validator is in
          the last group.
        <% else %>
          <i class="fas fa-circle score-<%= score %> mr-1"></i> (<%= score %> points) means that the&nbsp;validator is in
          the middle group.<br />
        <% end %>

        <% score -= 1 %>
      <% end %>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Vote Distance</strong> <br />
      The&nbsp;scoring rules are the&nbsp;same as Root Block Distance above. The validators are divided into <%= @groups_number %>
      equal groups based on their performance.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-<%= @max_score %> mr-1"></i> (<%= @max_score %> points) is the&nbsp;highest possible score in this category.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-0 mr-1"></i> (0 points) is the&nbsp;lowest possible score in this category.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Skipped Slot &percnt;</strong> <br />
      For this metric, we track a&nbsp;trailing 24-hour moving average of the&nbsp;skip rate. Validators are then divided into
      <%= @groups_number %> equal groups based on their moving average and the&nbsp;scores are assigned in the&nbsp;same manner
      as for Root Distance Score above.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-<%= @max_score %> mr-1"></i> (<%= @max_score %> points) is the&nbsp;highest possible score in this category.<br />
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-0 mr-1"></i> (0 points) is the&nbsp;lowest possible score in this category.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>Other metrics remain unchanged.</p>
  <p>
    The maximum score is currently <%= @max_total_score.humanize %> (<%= @max_total_score %>) points:
    <span class="text-nowrap">
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-<%= @max_score %>" title="Root Distance Score"></i>
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-<%= @max_score %>" title="Vote Distance Score"></i>
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-<%= @max_score %>" title="Skipped Slot Score"></i>
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-2" title="Published Information Score"></i>
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-2" title="Software Version Score"></i>
      <i class="fas fa-circle score-1" title="Security Report Score"></i>
    </span>
  </p>
</div>

<h3 class="h5" id="data-centers">Data Centers</h3>
<p class="mb-5">
  For the security reasons it is recommended that the validators in solana cluster are spread among as many
  locations as possible. It reduces the possibility of network collapse in case of a data center breakage.
  On our <%= link_to "data centers", data_centers_url(network: params[:network])%> page you can examine the validators
  distribution between data centers and organisations Autonomous System Numbers (ASN).
</p>

